var documenterSearchIndex = {"docs":
[{"category":"section","location":"methods_initialize/#Initialization","page":"Initialization","text":"\n\n\n\nIn this function, p4est is initialized. Mesh (in both physical and velocity space) is generated and adaptively refined. Field (in both physical and velocity space) is initialized according to initial conditions. Mapping between Julia data and p4est is established. Currently, realizations for 2D and 3D cases are different. The method for 3D case can be more complicated but more efficient. The method for 2D will be improved to be consistent with the 3D case.\n\n\n\nInitialize PsData and establish the mapping between Julia data and p4est.\n\n\n\nMesh identification, geometric adaptive refinement, and initial partition.\n\n\n\nInitialize faces defined by AbstractFace.\n\n\n\nInitialize the ghost layer in p4est.\n\n\n\nInitialize the mesh in p4est that is used to look up the neighboring cell in physical space.\n\n\n\nInitialize Neighbor in PsData.\n\n\n\nInitialize SolidNeighbors corresponding to the immersed boundaries.","title":"Initialization"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_initialize/#KitAMR.initialize_KitAMR","page":"Initialization","text":"initialize_KitAMR(\n    config::Dict\n) -> Tuple{Union{Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p4est}, Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p8est}}, KA}\n\n\nInitialize everthing according to config dictionary.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.initialize_KitAMR"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_initialize/#KitAMR.initialize_ghost","page":"Initialization","text":"initialize_ghost(\n    p4est::Union{Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p4est}, Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p8est}},\n    kinfo::KInfo\n) -> Ghost\n\n\nInitialize Ghost structure.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.initialize_ghost"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_initialize/#KitAMR.initialize_trees!","page":"Initialization","text":"initialize_trees!(\n    kinfo::KInfo{DIM, NDF}\n) -> Tuple{Union{Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p4est}, Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p8est}}, Any}\n\n\nInitialize field for 2D case.\n\n\n\n\n\ninitialize_trees!(\n    kinfo::KInfo{3, NDF}\n) -> Tuple{Union{Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p4est}, Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p8est}}, Any}\n\n\nInitialize field for 3D case.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.initialize_trees!"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_initialize/#KitAMR.initialize_ps!","page":"Initialization","text":"initialize_ps!(\n    p4est::Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p4est},\n    kinfo::KInfo{DIM, NDF}\n) -> PsTrees\n\n\n\n\n\n\ninitialize_ps!(\n    p4est::Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p8est},\n    kinfo::KInfo{DIM, NDF}\n) -> Any\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.initialize_ps!"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_initialize/#KitAMR.pre_refine!","page":"Initialization","text":"pre_refine!(\n    p4est::Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p4est},\n    kinfo::KInfo\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\npre_refine!(\n    p4est::Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p8est},\n    kinfo::KInfo\n) -> Any\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.pre_refine!"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_initialize/#KitAMR.initialize_faces!","page":"Initialization","text":"initialize_faces!(\n    p4est::Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p4est},\n    ka::KA\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\ninitialize_faces!(\n    p4est::Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p8est},\n    ka::KA\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.initialize_faces!"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_initialize/#KitAMR.AMR_ghost_new","page":"Initialization","text":"AMR_ghost_new(\n    p4est::Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p4est}\n) -> Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p4est_ghost_t}\n\n\n\n\n\n\nAMR_ghost_new(\n    p4est::Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p8est}\n) -> Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p8est_ghost_t}\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.AMR_ghost_new"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_initialize/#KitAMR.AMR_mesh_new","page":"Initialization","text":"AMR_mesh_new(\n    p4est::Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p4est},\n    ghost::Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p4est_ghost_t}\n) -> Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p4est_mesh_t}\n\n\n\n\n\n\nAMR_mesh_new(\n    p4est::Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p8est},\n    ghost::Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p8est_ghost_t}\n) -> Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p8est_mesh_t}\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.AMR_mesh_new"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_initialize/#KitAMR.initialize_neighbor_data!","page":"Initialization","text":"initialize_neighbor_data!(\n    ip::KitAMR.P4est.PointerWrappers.PointerWrapper{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p4est_iter_volume_info},\n    data,\n    dp\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\ninitialize_neighbor_data!(\n    ip::KitAMR.P4est.PointerWrappers.PointerWrapper{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p8est_iter_volume_info},\n    data,\n    dp\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\ninitialize_neighbor_data!(info, data)\n\n\n\n\n\n\ninitialize_neighbor_data!(\n    p4est::Union{Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p4est}, Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p8est}},\n    ka::KA\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.initialize_neighbor_data!"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_initialize/#KitAMR.initialize_solid_neighbor!","page":"Initialization","text":"initialize_solid_neighbor!(ka::KA)\n\n\n\n\n\n\ninitialize_solid_neighbor!(\n    ps_data::PsData{DIM, NDF},\n    ka::KA{DIM, NDF}\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.initialize_solid_neighbor!"},{"category":"section","location":"type_configure/#Configuration","page":"Configuration","text":"To simulate a problem using KitAMR, user is required to define the problem. Most of the user-provided information is collected in Configure struct. ","title":"Configuration"},{"category":"type","location":"type_configure/#KitAMR.Configure","page":"Configuration","text":"struct Configure{DIM, NDF}\n\nStructure of problem configuration. DIM and NDF represent the dimension number of the problem and the number of the distribution function. This struct plays an key role in the solution process.\n\nFields\n\ngeometry::Vector{Float64}: Range of the simulated domain. As an example, for 2D case, it should be aligned as [xmin,xmax,ymin,ymax].\ntrees_num::Vector{Int64}: Number of tree roots for each dimension. For 2D case, it should be aligned as [xnum,ynum]\nquadrature::Union{KitAMR.AbstractQuadrature, Vector{Float64}}: For Vector type, it represents the range of the velocity space. For 2D case, it should be aligned as [umin,umax,vmin,vmax]. The AbstractQuadrature type is reserved for other quadrature rule like Gauss-Hermite.\nvs_trees_num::Vector{Int64}: Number of tree roots for each dimension in velocity space.\nIC::AbstractInitCond: Initial condition defined by AbstractInitCond.\ndomain::Vector{Domain}: Types of the domain boundary. For 2D case, the vector should catain 4 elements corresponding to the 4 domain boundaries. The element type is defined by Domain.\nIB::Vector{AbstractBoundary}: Immersed boundary. Multiple boundaries are supported. The element type is defined by AbstractBoundary\ngas::Gas: Properties of the simulated gas defined by Gas.\nsolver::Solver: Setup of the solver defined by Solver.\noutput::Output: Setup of the output form defined by Output.\nuser_defined::UDF: Functions defined by users, including some criteria.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.Configure"},{"category":"type","location":"type_configure/#KitAMR.Solver","page":"Configuration","text":"struct Solver{DIM, NDF}\n\nStructure of solver configuration.\n\nFields\n\nCFL::Float64: Courant-Friedrichs-Lewy number. Default is 0.4.\nAMR_PS_MAXLEVEL::Int64: Maximum level of the (static) AMR in physical space. Mandatory.\nAMR_DYNAMIC_PS_MAXLEVEL::Int64: Maximum level of the dynamic AMR in physical space. In most cases, it should be smaller than the static one. Default is equal to AMR_PS_MAXLEVEL.\nAMR_VS_MAXLEVEL::Int64: Maximum level of the AMR in velocity space. Mandatory.\nflux::Type{Tf} where Tf<:AbstractFluxType: Numerical flux type. Mandatory.\ntime_marching::Type{Tt} where Tt<:AbstractTimeMarchingType: Time-marching scheme. Mandatory.\nPS_DYNAMIC_AMR::Bool: Dynamic AMR in physical space is open or not. Default is true.\nVS_DYNAMIC_AMR::Bool: Dynamic AMR in velocity space is open or not. Default is true.\nADAPT_COEFFI_PS::Float64: Redundancy coefficient of AMR in physical space. Default is 0.25.\nADAPT_COEFFI_VS_GLOBAL::Float64: Redundancy coefficient of AMR in velocity space. Default is 0.125.\nADAPT_COEFFI_VS_LOCAL::Float64: Proportion that a refinement-required velocity cell contributes to the macroscopic quantities in a local physical cell. Default is 0.01.\nTOLERANCE::Float64: Tolerance for convergence judgement. Default is 1e-6.\nST_CHECK_INTERVAL::Int64: Number of steps between two checks of status. Default is 100.\nREDUNDANT_STEPS_NUM::Int64: Number of redundant steps after convergence criterion has been satisfied. Default is 100.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.Solver"},{"category":"type","location":"type_configure/#KitAMR.UDF","page":"Configuration","text":"mutable struct UDF\n\nStructure of user-defined-functions.\n\nFields\n\nstatic_ps_refine_flag::Function: The static AMR flag in physical space. (midpoint::Vector{Float64},ds::Vector{Float64},kinfo::KInfo,level::Int)->Bool\ndynamic_ps_refine_flag::Function: The dynamic AMR flag in physical space. (ps_data::AbstractPsData,level::Int,ka::KA)->Bool\nstatic_vs_refine_flag::Function: The static AMR flag in velocity space.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.UDF"},{"category":"section","location":"limitations/#Limitations","page":"Limitations","text":"In current stage, KitAMR.jl has several noticeable limitations, including\n\nFlows with volume forces (which will introduce derivatives with respect to velocity coordinates) are not supported.\nOnly translational non-equilibrium effects is introduced.\nOnly support fully diffuse Maxwellian gas-surface interaction model.\nRestart is not supported in consideration of the enormous size of data in complete phase space.\nOnly support Euler method for time marching, which only exhibits first order accuracy. For transient problems, higher order time marching scheme is required to be consistent with spatial and quadrature accuracy.\n\nAny contribution is welcomed. Please feel free to ask us questions and chat with us at any time if you're unsure about anything.","title":"Limitations"},{"category":"section","location":"type_data/#Data","page":"Data","text":"All of the data in KitAMR.jl are organized as follows:","title":"Data"},{"category":"type","location":"type_data/#KitAMR.KA","page":"Data","text":"mutable struct KA{DIM, NDF}\n\nStructure that collects all of the data.\n\nkinfo::KInfo\nkdata::KData\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.KA"},{"category":"type","location":"type_data/#KitAMR.KInfo","page":"Data","text":"mutable struct KInfo{DIM, NDF}\n\nStructure of required information during a simulation.\n\nconfig::Configure: Defined by Configure.\nforest::Forest: Defined by Forest.\nstatus::Status: Defined by Status.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.KInfo"},{"category":"type","location":"type_data/#KitAMR.KData","page":"Data","text":"mutable struct KData{DIM, NDF}\n\nStructure of computed data.\n\nfield::Field\nghost::Ghost\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.KData"},{"category":"type","location":"type_data/#KitAMR.Forest","page":"Data","text":"mutable struct Forest{DIM}\n\nStructure related to p4est.\n\np4est::Union{Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p4est}, Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p8est}}\nghost::Union{Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p4est_ghost_t}, Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p8est_ghost_t}}\nmesh::Union{Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p4est_mesh_t}, Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p8est_mesh_t}}\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.Forest"},{"category":"type","location":"type_data/#KitAMR.Status","page":"Data","text":"mutable struct Status\n\nStructure of simulation status. It contains the real time information, and is updated every step.\n\nFields\n\ngradmax::Vector{Float64}: Maximum absolute value of the gradients of conserved variables.\nΔt::Float64: Time step size used in iterate!.\nΔt_ξ::Float64: Time step size constraint by grid size.\nsim_time::Float64: Dimensionless simulation time.\nstep::Int64: Number of steps that have been marched.\nps_adapt_step::Int64: Number of steps after last AMR in physical space.\nvs_adapt_step::Int64: Number of steps after last AMR in velocity space.\npartition_step::Int64: Number of steps after last partition.\nresidual::Residual: Residual of conserved variables defined by Residual.\nsave_flag::Base.RefValue{Bool}: Flag indicating whether to save.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.Status"},{"category":"type","location":"type_data/#KitAMR.Residual","page":"Data","text":"mutable struct Residual\n\nresidual::Vector{Float64}: Residual of primary variables, is updated by residual_check!.\nsumRes::Vector{Float64}: Summation of residuals.\nsumAvg::Vector{Float64}: Summation of primary variables to average sumRes.\nredundant_step::Int64: Count of redundant step to insure the convergence.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.Residual"},{"category":"type","location":"type_data/#KitAMR.Ghost","page":"Data","text":"mutable struct Ghost\n\nStructure of ghost layer for communication between processors.\n\nghost_buffer::GhostBuffer\nghost_wrap::Vector{KitAMR.AbstractGhostPsData}\nghost_info::GhostInfo\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.Ghost"},{"category":"type","location":"type_data/#KitAMR.GhostBuffer","page":"Data","text":"mutable struct GhostBuffer\n\nJulia-managed MPI buffers for the ghost layer.  All memory is owned by the Julia GC; no manual sc_free is required.\n\nghost_datas::Vector{Float64}: Flat receive buffer for ghost cell data (df, w, …).\nghost_slopes::Vector{Float64}: Flat receive buffer for ghost cell slopes (sdf, sw).\nghost_structures::Vector{Float64}: Flat receive buffer for ghost VS structure (weight, level, midpoint).\nmirror_data_bufs::Vector{Vector{Float64}}: Per-mirror send buffer for data, one entry per mirror quadrant.\nmirror_slope_bufs::Vector{Vector{Float64}}: Per-mirror send buffer for slopes, one entry per mirror quadrant.\nmirror_structure_bufs::Vector{Vector{Float64}}: Per-mirror send buffer for VS structure, one entry per mirror quadrant.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.GhostBuffer"},{"category":"type","location":"type_data/#KitAMR.GhostInfo","page":"Data","text":"struct GhostInfo\n\nJulia-managed metadata for the ghost layer: vs_nums, flat-buffer offsets, and pre-computed element-count arrays that are reused every time-step without reallocation.\n\nghost_vsnums::Vector{Int64}: vsnum of each ghost quadrant (length = nghosts).\nmirror_vsnums::Vector{Int64}: vsnum of each mirror quadrant (length = nmirrors).\nghost_data_offsets::Vector{Int64}: Float64-element offset into ghost_datas for each ghost quadrant.\nghost_slope_offsets::Vector{Int64}: Float64-element offset into ghost_slopes for each ghost quadrant.\nghost_structure_offsets::Vector{Int64}: Float64-element offset into ghost_structures for each ghost quadrant.\nghost_data_szs::Vector{Int64}: Cached Float64-element count of ghost data buffer per ghost quadrant.\nghost_slope_szs::Vector{Int64}: Cached Float64-element count of ghost slope buffer per ghost quadrant.\nmirror_data_szs::Vector{Int64}: Cached Float64-element count of ghost data buffer per mirror quadrant.\nmirror_slope_szs::Vector{Int64}: Cached Float64-element count of ghost slope buffer per mirror quadrant.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.GhostInfo"},{"category":"type","location":"type_data/#KitAMR.Field","page":"Data","text":"mutable struct Field{DIM, NDF}\n\nStructure of fields data.\n\ntrees::PsTrees: Cells data defined by PsTrees.\nfaces::Vector{AbstractFace}: Mapping between faces and cells. The element type is defined by AbstractFace.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.Field"},{"category":"type","location":"type_data/#KitAMR.PsTrees","page":"Data","text":"mutable struct PsTrees{DIM, NDF}\n\nStructure of cells data managed by Julia.\n\ndata::Array{Array{AbstractPsData{DIM, NDF}, 1}, 1} where {DIM, NDF}\noffset::Int64: Offset of treeid used in partition.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.PsTrees"},{"category":"section","location":"methods_reconstruct/#Reconstruction","page":"Reconstruction","text":"","title":"Reconstruction"},{"category":"section","location":"methods_reconstruct/#Slope","page":"Reconstruction","text":"In current version, the distribution function is reconstructed as a linear function. Besides the function value at center of the cell, the slope is also required. The slope is obtained by finite difference. To eliminate the oscillation near discontinuities, the vanLeer limiter is adopted. \n\n\n\nThe finite difference is not that simple considering cells in templates may exhibit different refinement level, in both physical and velocity space. Here we list related methods. For more detailed explanation, one may refer to our future paper.\n\n\n\nOuter function to update sdf in VsData and sw in PsData.\n\n\n\nHere are methods corresponding to different cases in physical space. The first two argument types refer to the number of the neighboring cells in negative and positive direction along the dirth dimension. Val{i} refers to there are i neighboring cells across the face. -1 represents a single cell with lower refinement level. Because the mesh is balanced, only following cases are required to consider.\n\nUpdate both micro and macro slopes in cells neighboring to domain edges. \n\n\n\nUpdate both micro and macro in internal cells.\n\n\n\nUpdate micro slope sdf.\n\n\n\nUpdate macro slope sw. Currently, sw is only used as an indicator for AMR in physical space. Hence, the calculation is carried out without a limiter. On the contrary, the slope with larger absolute value in two sides slopes is adopted for more sufficient refinement.\n\n\n\nTo preserve the positivity of the distribution function, a positivity-preserving reconstruction strategy is adopted. Detailed information is in Flux.","title":"Slope"},{"category":"section","location":"methods_reconstruct/#Immersed-boundary-method","page":"Reconstruction","text":"Boundaries with complex geometry are resolved with immersed boundary method. More specifically, a sharp interface method with ghost cell is adopted. Detailed information can be found in our paper https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.2512.20252. KitAMR.jl provided interfaces for the reconstruction of the ghost cells","title":"Immersed boundary method"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_reconstruct/#KitAMR.vanleer","page":"Reconstruction","text":"vanleer(sL::AbstractArray, sR::AbstractArray) -> Any\n\n\n\n\n\n\nvanleer(sL::Real, sR::Real) -> Any\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.vanleer"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_reconstruct/#KitAMR.diff_vs!","page":"Reconstruction","text":"diff_vs!(\n    vs_data::AbstractVsData{DIM, NDF},\n    vs_data_n::AbstractVsData{DIM, NDF},\n    dsL::Float64,\n    sL::AbstractMatrix\n)\n\n\nDifference through all velocity cells in two neighboring physical cells.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.diff_vs!"},{"category":"method","location":"methods_reconstruct/#KitAMR.update_slope!-Union{Tuple{KA{DIM, NDF}}, Tuple{NDF}, Tuple{DIM}} where {DIM, NDF}","page":"Reconstruction","text":"update_slope!(ka::KA{DIM, NDF})\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.update_slope!"},{"category":"method","location":"methods_reconstruct/#KitAMR.update_slope!-Tuple{Val{0}, Val{1}, PsData, KInfo, AbstractVector, AbstractVector, Integer, Matrix{Float64}, Matrix{Float64}, Vector{Float64}, Vector{Float64}}","page":"Reconstruction","text":"update_slope!(\n    _::Val{0},\n    _::Val{1},\n    ps_data::PsData,\n    kinfo::KInfo{DIM, NDF},\n    Ldata::AbstractVector,\n    Rdata::AbstractVector,\n    dir::Integer,\n    ws_sL::Matrix{Float64},\n    ws_sR::Matrix{Float64},\n    ws_swL::Vector{Float64},\n    ws_swR::Vector{Float64}\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.update_slope!"},{"category":"method","location":"methods_reconstruct/#KitAMR.update_slope!-Tuple{Val{1}, Val{0}, PsData, KInfo, AbstractVector, AbstractVector, Integer, Matrix{Float64}, Matrix{Float64}, Vector{Float64}, Vector{Float64}}","page":"Reconstruction","text":"update_slope!(\n    _::Val{1},\n    _::Val{0},\n    ps_data::PsData,\n    kinfo::KInfo{DIM, NDF},\n    Ldata::AbstractVector,\n    Rdata::AbstractVector,\n    dir::Integer,\n    ws_sL::Matrix{Float64},\n    ws_sR::Matrix{Float64},\n    ws_swL::Vector{Float64},\n    ws_swR::Vector{Float64}\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.update_slope!"},{"category":"method","location":"methods_reconstruct/#KitAMR.update_slope!-Tuple{Val{0}, Val{-1}, PsData, KInfo, AbstractVector, AbstractVector, Integer, Matrix{Float64}, Matrix{Float64}, Vector{Float64}, Vector{Float64}}","page":"Reconstruction","text":"update_slope!(\n    _::Val{0},\n    _::Val{-1},\n    ps_data::PsData,\n    kinfo::KInfo{DIM, NDF},\n    Ldata::AbstractVector,\n    Rdata::AbstractVector,\n    dir::Integer,\n    ws_sL::Matrix{Float64},\n    ws_sR::Matrix{Float64},\n    ws_swL::Vector{Float64},\n    ws_swR::Vector{Float64}\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.update_slope!"},{"category":"method","location":"methods_reconstruct/#KitAMR.update_slope!-Tuple{Val{-1}, Val{0}, PsData, KInfo, AbstractVector, AbstractVector, Integer, Matrix{Float64}, Matrix{Float64}, Vector{Float64}, Vector{Float64}}","page":"Reconstruction","text":"update_slope!(\n    _::Val{-1},\n    _::Val{0},\n    ps_data::PsData,\n    kinfo::KInfo{DIM, NDF},\n    Ldata::AbstractVector,\n    Rdata::AbstractVector,\n    dir::Integer,\n    ws_sL::Matrix{Float64},\n    ws_sR::Matrix{Float64},\n    ws_swL::Vector{Float64},\n    ws_swR::Vector{Float64}\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.update_slope!"},{"category":"method","location":"methods_reconstruct/#KitAMR.update_slope!-Tuple{Val{0}, Union{Val{2}, Val{4}}, PsData, KInfo, AbstractVector, AbstractVector, Integer, Matrix{Float64}, Matrix{Float64}, Vector{Float64}, Vector{Float64}}","page":"Reconstruction","text":"update_slope!(\n    _::Val{0},\n    _::Union{Val{2}, Val{4}},\n    ps_data::PsData,\n    kinfo::KInfo{DIM, NDF},\n    Ldata::AbstractVector,\n    Rdata::AbstractVector,\n    dir::Integer,\n    ws_sL::Matrix{Float64},\n    ws_sR::Matrix{Float64},\n    ws_swL::Vector{Float64},\n    ws_swR::Vector{Float64}\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.update_slope!"},{"category":"method","location":"methods_reconstruct/#KitAMR.update_slope!-Tuple{Union{Val{2}, Val{4}}, Val{0}, PsData, KInfo, AbstractVector, AbstractVector, Integer, Matrix{Float64}, Matrix{Float64}, Vector{Float64}, Vector{Float64}}","page":"Reconstruction","text":"update_slope!(\n    _::Union{Val{2}, Val{4}},\n    _::Val{0},\n    ps_data::PsData,\n    kinfo::KInfo{DIM, NDF},\n    Ldata::AbstractVector,\n    Rdata::AbstractVector,\n    dir::Integer,\n    ws_sL::Matrix{Float64},\n    ws_sR::Matrix{Float64},\n    ws_swL::Vector{Float64},\n    ws_swR::Vector{Float64}\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.update_slope!"},{"category":"method","location":"methods_reconstruct/#KitAMR.update_slope!-Tuple{Val{1}, Val{1}, PsData, KInfo, AbstractVector, AbstractVector, Integer, Matrix{Float64}, Matrix{Float64}, Vector{Float64}, Vector{Float64}}","page":"Reconstruction","text":"update_slope!(\n    _::Val{1},\n    _::Val{1},\n    ps_data::PsData,\n    kinfo::KInfo{DIM, NDF},\n    Ldata::AbstractVector,\n    Rdata::AbstractVector,\n    dir::Integer,\n    ws_sL::Matrix{Float64},\n    ws_sR::Matrix{Float64},\n    ws_swL::Vector{Float64},\n    ws_swR::Vector{Float64}\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.update_slope!"},{"category":"method","location":"methods_reconstruct/#KitAMR.update_slope!-Tuple{Val{1}, Val{-1}, PsData, KInfo, AbstractVector, AbstractVector, Integer, Matrix{Float64}, Matrix{Float64}, Vector{Float64}, Vector{Float64}}","page":"Reconstruction","text":"update_slope!(\n    _::Val{1},\n    _::Val{-1},\n    ps_data::PsData,\n    kinfo::KInfo{DIM, NDF},\n    Ldata::AbstractVector,\n    Rdata::AbstractVector,\n    dir::Integer,\n    ws_sL::Matrix{Float64},\n    ws_sR::Matrix{Float64},\n    ws_swL::Vector{Float64},\n    ws_swR::Vector{Float64}\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.update_slope!"},{"category":"method","location":"methods_reconstruct/#KitAMR.update_slope!-Tuple{Val{-1}, Val{1}, PsData, KInfo, AbstractVector, AbstractVector, Integer, Matrix{Float64}, Matrix{Float64}, Vector{Float64}, Vector{Float64}}","page":"Reconstruction","text":"update_slope!(\n    _::Val{-1},\n    _::Val{1},\n    ps_data::PsData,\n    kinfo::KInfo{DIM, NDF},\n    Ldata::AbstractVector,\n    Rdata::AbstractVector,\n    dir::Integer,\n    ws_sL::Matrix{Float64},\n    ws_sR::Matrix{Float64},\n    ws_swL::Vector{Float64},\n    ws_swR::Vector{Float64}\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.update_slope!"},{"category":"method","location":"methods_reconstruct/#KitAMR.update_slope!-Tuple{Val{1}, Union{Val{2}, Val{4}}, PsData, KInfo, AbstractVector, AbstractVector, Integer, Matrix{Float64}, Matrix{Float64}, Vector{Float64}, Vector{Float64}}","page":"Reconstruction","text":"update_slope!(\n    _::Val{1},\n    _::Union{Val{2}, Val{4}},\n    ps_data::PsData,\n    kinfo::KInfo{DIM, NDF},\n    Ldata::AbstractVector,\n    Rdata::AbstractVector,\n    dir::Integer,\n    ws_sL::Matrix{Float64},\n    ws_sR::Matrix{Float64},\n    ws_swL::Vector{Float64},\n    ws_swR::Vector{Float64}\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.update_slope!"},{"category":"method","location":"methods_reconstruct/#KitAMR.update_slope!-Tuple{Union{Val{2}, Val{4}}, Val{1}, PsData, KInfo, AbstractVector, AbstractVector, Integer, Matrix{Float64}, Matrix{Float64}, Vector{Float64}, Vector{Float64}}","page":"Reconstruction","text":"update_slope!(\n    _::Union{Val{2}, Val{4}},\n    _::Val{1},\n    ps_data::PsData,\n    kinfo::KInfo{DIM, NDF},\n    Ldata::AbstractVector,\n    Rdata::AbstractVector,\n    dir::Integer,\n    ws_sL::Matrix{Float64},\n    ws_sR::Matrix{Float64},\n    ws_swL::Vector{Float64},\n    ws_swR::Vector{Float64}\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.update_slope!"},{"category":"method","location":"methods_reconstruct/#KitAMR.update_slope!-Tuple{Val{-1}, Union{Val{2}, Val{4}}, PsData, KInfo, AbstractVector, AbstractVector, Integer, Matrix{Float64}, Matrix{Float64}, Vector{Float64}, Vector{Float64}}","page":"Reconstruction","text":"update_slope!(\n    _::Val{-1},\n    _::Union{Val{2}, Val{4}},\n    ps_data::PsData,\n    kinfo::KInfo{DIM, NDF},\n    Ldata::AbstractVector,\n    Rdata::AbstractVector,\n    dir::Integer,\n    ws_sL::Matrix{Float64},\n    ws_sR::Matrix{Float64},\n    ws_swL::Vector{Float64},\n    ws_swR::Vector{Float64}\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.update_slope!"},{"category":"method","location":"methods_reconstruct/#KitAMR.update_slope!-Tuple{Union{Val{2}, Val{4}}, Val{-1}, PsData, KInfo, AbstractVector, AbstractVector, Integer, Matrix{Float64}, Matrix{Float64}, Vector{Float64}, Vector{Float64}}","page":"Reconstruction","text":"update_slope!(\n    _::Union{Val{2}, Val{4}},\n    _::Val{-1},\n    ps_data::PsData,\n    kinfo::KInfo{DIM, NDF},\n    Ldata::AbstractVector,\n    Rdata::AbstractVector,\n    dir::Integer,\n    ws_sL::Matrix{Float64},\n    ws_sR::Matrix{Float64},\n    ws_swL::Vector{Float64},\n    ws_swR::Vector{Float64}\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.update_slope!"},{"category":"method","location":"methods_reconstruct/#KitAMR.update_slope!-Tuple{Union{Val{2}, Val{4}}, Union{Val{2}, Val{4}}, PsData, KInfo, AbstractVector, AbstractVector, Integer, Matrix{Float64}, Matrix{Float64}, Vector{Float64}, Vector{Float64}}","page":"Reconstruction","text":"update_slope!(\n    _::Union{Val{2}, Val{4}},\n    _::Union{Val{2}, Val{4}},\n    ps_data::PsData,\n    kinfo::KInfo{DIM, NDF},\n    Ldata::AbstractVector,\n    Rdata::AbstractVector,\n    dir::Integer,\n    ws_sL::Matrix{Float64},\n    ws_sR::Matrix{Float64},\n    ws_swL::Vector{Float64},\n    ws_swR::Vector{Float64}\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.update_slope!"},{"category":"method","location":"methods_reconstruct/#KitAMR.update_slope!-Tuple{Val{-1}, Val{-1}, PsData, KInfo, AbstractVector, AbstractVector, Integer, Matrix{Float64}, Matrix{Float64}, Vector{Float64}, Vector{Float64}}","page":"Reconstruction","text":"update_slope!(\n    _::Val{-1},\n    _::Val{-1},\n    ps_data::PsData,\n    kinfo::KInfo{DIM, NDF},\n    Ldata::AbstractVector,\n    Rdata::AbstractVector,\n    dir::Integer,\n    ws_sL::Matrix{Float64},\n    ws_sR::Matrix{Float64},\n    ws_swL::Vector{Float64},\n    ws_swR::Vector{Float64}\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.update_slope!"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_reconstruct/#KitAMR.update_slope_inner_vs!","page":"Reconstruction","text":"update_slope_inner_vs!(\n    vs_data::AbstractVsData{DIM, NDF},\n    Ldata::Vector,\n    Rdata::Vector,\n    dsL::Float64,\n    dsR::Float64,\n    dir::Int64,\n    ws_sL::Matrix{Float64},\n    ws_sR::Matrix{Float64}\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.update_slope_inner_vs!"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_reconstruct/#KitAMR.update_slope_bound_vs!","page":"Reconstruction","text":"update_slope_bound_vs!(\n    vs_data::AbstractVsData{DIM, NDF},\n    neighbor_datas::AbstractVector,\n    ds::Float64,\n    dir::Int64,\n    ws_sdf::Matrix{Float64}\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.update_slope_bound_vs!"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_reconstruct/#KitAMR.update_slope_inner_ps!","page":"Reconstruction","text":"update_slope_inner_ps!(\n    ps_data::PsData{DIM, NDF},\n    Ldata::AbstractVector,\n    Rdata::AbstractVector,\n    dsL::Float64,\n    dsR::Float64,\n    dir::Int64,\n    ws_swL::Vector{Float64},\n    ws_swR::Vector{Float64}\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.update_slope_inner_ps!"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_reconstruct/#KitAMR.update_slope_bound_ps!","page":"Reconstruction","text":"update_slope_bound_ps!(\n    ps_data::PsData{DIM, NDF},\n    Ldata::AbstractVector,\n    dsL::Float64,\n    dir::Int64,\n    ws_swL::Vector{Float64}\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.update_slope_bound_ps!"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_reconstruct/#KitAMR.update_solid_cell!","page":"Reconstruction","text":"update_solid_cell!(ka::KA)\n\n\nUpdate solid_cell in SolidNeighbor with interpolation.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.update_solid_cell!"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_reconstruct/#KitAMR.update_solid_neighbor!","page":"Reconstruction","text":"update_solid_neighbor!(ka::KA{DIM, NDF})\n\n\nUpdate VsData variables in SolidNeighbor with the immersed boundary method.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.update_solid_neighbor!"},{"category":"section","location":"methods_theory/#Theory","page":"Theory","text":"The backend functions related to kinetic theory are integrated in lib/KitCore. Some interfaces are provided","title":"Theory"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_theory/#KitAMR.get_prim","page":"Theory","text":"get_prim(\n    ps_data::PsData{2, NDF},\n    kinfo::KInfo{2, NDF}\n) -> Vector{Float64}\n\n\nGet primary macroscopic variables from the conserved variables.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.get_prim"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_theory/#KitAMR.get_conserved","page":"Theory","text":"get_conserved(\n    ps_data::PsData{2, NDF},\n    kinfo::KInfo\n) -> Vector{Float64}\n\n\nGet conserved macroscopic variables from the primary variables.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.get_conserved"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_theory/#KitAMR.calc_w0","page":"Theory","text":"calc_w0(\n    midpoint::AbstractMatrix,\n    df::AbstractMatrix,\n    weight::AbstractVector,\n    _::KInfo{2, 2}\n) -> Vector\n\n\nCalculate the conserved macroscopic variables according to the microscopic distribution.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.calc_w0"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_theory/#KitAMR.calc_qf","page":"Theory","text":"calc_qf(\n    vs_data::AbstractVsData{2, 2},\n    prim::AbstractVector\n) -> Vector\n\n\nCalculate the heat flux according to the microscopic distribution.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.calc_qf"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_theory/#KitAMR.discrete_maxwell","page":"Theory","text":"discrete_maxwell(\n    ps_data::PsData,\n    kinfo::KInfo\n) -> Matrix{Float64}\n\n\nCaculate the discretized Maxwellian distribution according to the primary macroscopic variables.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.discrete_maxwell"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_theory/#KitAMR.shakhov_part","page":"Theory","text":"shakhov_part(\n    midpoint::AbstractMatrix,\n    F::AbstractMatrix,\n    prim::AbstractVector,\n    qf::AbstractVector,\n    kinfo::KInfo{2, 2}\n) -> Union{Matrix, Vector{Float64}}\n\n\nCalculate the discretized Shakhov correction.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.shakhov_part"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_theory/#KitAMR.ref_vhs_vis","page":"Theory","text":"ref_vhs_vis(Kn, omega) -> Any\nref_vhs_vis(Kn, omega, alpha) -> Any\nref_vhs_vis(Kn, omega, alpha, T_ref) -> Any\n\n\nReference viscousity obtained by VHS molecules model.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.ref_vhs_vis"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_theory/#KitAMR.get_τ","page":"Theory","text":"get_τ(prim::AbstractVector, μ::Real, ω::Real) -> Any\n\n\nCalculate collisional time.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.get_τ"},{"category":"section","location":"type_output/#Output-configuration","page":"Output","text":"KitAMR.jl outputs the field as .jld2 and .pvtu files for post-processing.\n\nSupported vtk cell types are\n\nNote that the vertices in .pvtu file are redundant. To obtain contour of the field, a cleaning process in post-process software is required. For example, using Paraview, one needs to execute Clean to Grid before contour.\n\nTriangle and Tetra are chosen for smoother field visualization, but will not improve the accuracy of the solution. The variables on their vertices are linearly reconstructed. ","title":"Output configuration"},{"category":"type","location":"type_output/#KitAMR.Output","page":"Output","text":"mutable struct Output\n\nStructure of output information.\n\nFields\n\nvtk_celltype::Type{Tp} where Tp<:KitAMR.AbstractVTKCellType: VTK cell type in physical space. Available options: Pixel and Triangle for 2D; Voxel and Tetra for 3D. Default is Triangle for 2D and Tetra for 3D.\nvs_vtk_celltype::Type{Tv} where Tv<:KitAMR.AbstractVTKCellType: VTK cell type in velocity space. Available options: Pixel for 2D.\nanim_dt::Float64: Time interval between animation frames.\nvs_output_criterion::Function: User-defined-function determining the physical cells need to output the velocity space.\nanim_index::Int64: Index of the last saved animation frame.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.Output"},{"category":"type","location":"type_output/#KitAMR.Pixel","page":"Output","text":"abstract type Pixel <: KitAMR.AbstractVTKCellType\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.Pixel"},{"category":"type","location":"type_output/#KitAMR.Voxel","page":"Output","text":"abstract type Voxel <: KitAMR.AbstractVTKCellType\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.Voxel"},{"category":"type","location":"type_output/#KitAMR.Triangle","page":"Output","text":"abstract type Triangle <: KitAMR.AbstractVTKCellType\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.Triangle"},{"category":"type","location":"type_output/#KitAMR.Tetra","page":"Output","text":"abstract type Tetra <: KitAMR.AbstractVTKCellType\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.Tetra"},{"category":"section","location":"methods_io/#IO","page":"IO","text":"","title":"IO"},{"category":"section","location":"methods_io/#Input","page":"IO","text":"todo: Todo\nA bug exists here, which causes the save input will not be aware of, until one stdout is invoked.","title":"Input"},{"category":"section","location":"methods_io/#Output","page":"IO","text":"","title":"Output"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_io/#KitAMR.read_config","page":"IO","text":"read_config(filename::AbstractString) -> Dict{Symbol, Any}\n\n\nRead .txt configuration file and return a dictionary.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.read_config"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_io/#KitAMR.listen_for_save!","page":"IO","text":"listen_for_save!(; rank)\n\n\nStart listening for the input from command line. Must be called before calling check_for_save!.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.listen_for_save!"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_io/#KitAMR.check_for_save!","page":"IO","text":"check_for_save!(p4est, ka; rank)\n\n\nCheck whether save is input during the iteration. If the result is true, a saving process will be executed.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.check_for_save!"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_io/#KitAMR.save_result","page":"IO","text":"save_result(\n    p4est::Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p4est},\n    ka::KA{DIM, NDF};\n    dir_path\n)\n\n\nSave all results to dir_path. If isempty(dir_path) is true, a folder named result<yyyy-mm-dd_HH-MM> will be made in current path.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.save_result"},{"category":"section","location":"methods_parallel/#Parallel","page":"Parallel","text":"During a simulation with distributed parallel, the communication among processors is crucial. In KitAMR.jl, the communication is supported by MPI.jl.","title":"Parallel"},{"category":"section","location":"methods_parallel/#Ghost-layers","page":"Parallel","text":"KitAMR.jl decomposes the computational domain in physical space. With explicit spatial discretization, the update of a cell only depends on its neighboring cells. If some of these neighboring cells lie on other processors, they are locally marked as ghost. The variables of the ghost cells are updated by MPI communication. Related functions are\n\nIn contrast to traditional CFD solver, KitAMR.jl also discretizes velocity space. The resolution of this discretization varies as time and physical coordinates changes. This results in the size of communicated data changing. Currently, the size of the communicated data is unified to hold the largest velocity space that exists in ghost layers. The size is obtained by\n\nWhether a unified communication size decreases the efficiency noticeably still requires testing.","title":"Ghost layers"},{"category":"section","location":"methods_parallel/#Partition","page":"Parallel","text":"After an AMR process, the grids density on different processors may changes a lot. To balance the load, partition can be performed by calling\n\nThe grids in physical space are encoded as a 1-dimensional sequence by Morton code, and then partitioned according to the weight provided by\n\nThe backend functions are provided by p4est, insuring high efficiency. \n\nWhen the partition is finished, a data exchange process is performed to transfer all of the data to where it is required. The communication only occurs to those partitioned cells.\n\nAll of the functionalities are wrapped into","title":"Partition"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_parallel/#KitAMR.data_exchange!","page":"Parallel","text":"data_exchange!(\n    p4est::Union{Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p4est}, Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p8est}},\n    ka::KA{DIM, NDF}\n)\n\n\nUpdate df in GhostVsData.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.data_exchange!"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_parallel/#KitAMR.slope_exchange!","page":"Parallel","text":"slope_exchange!(\n    p4est::Union{Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p4est}, Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p8est}},\n    ka::KA{DIM, NDF}\n)\n\n\nUpdate sdf in GhostVsData.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.slope_exchange!"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_parallel/#KitAMR.solid_exchange!","page":"Parallel","text":"solid_exchange!(\n    p4est::Union{Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p4est}, Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p8est}},\n    ka::KA{DIM, NDF}\n)\n\n\nUpdate df in GhostVsData for immersed-boundary cells only.\n\nOnly ghost cells with bound_enc < 0 (solid-adjacent, non-InsideSolid) are communicated; all other ghost cells are skipped, reducing both message sizes and the number of communicated elements compared to a full data_exchange!.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.solid_exchange!"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_parallel/#KitAMR.get_vs_num","page":"Parallel","text":"get_vs_num(\n    forest::Union{Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p4est}, Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p8est}},\n    ghost::Union{Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p4est_ghost_t}, Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p8est_ghost_t}}\n) -> Any\n\n\nGet the globally largest number of the velocity cells among all local and ghost quadrants.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.get_vs_num"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_parallel/#KitAMR.partition!","page":"Parallel","text":"partition!(\n    p4est::Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p4est}\n) -> Tuple{Vector{Int64}, Vector{Int64}, Int32, Int32}\npartition!(\n    p4est::Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p4est},\n    weight::Function\n) -> Tuple{Vector{Int64}, Vector{Int64}, Int32, Int32}\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.partition!"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_parallel/#KitAMR.partition_weight","page":"Parallel","text":"partition_weight(\n    p4est::Union{Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p4est}, Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p8est}},\n    which_tree,\n    quadrant::Union{Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p4est_quadrant}, Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p8est_quadrant}}\n) -> Any\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.partition_weight"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_parallel/#KitAMR.ps_partition!","page":"Parallel","text":"ps_partition!(\n    p4est::Union{Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p4est}, Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p8est}},\n    ka::KA\n)\n\n\nRe-partition grids in physical space to balance the computational load according to the weight function.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.ps_partition!"},{"category":"section","location":"index_internal/#Index","page":"Index","text":"","title":"Index"},{"category":"section","location":"type_physical_space/#Physical-space","page":"Physical space","text":"Information in physical space are organized as following.\n\nTo calculate the numerical flux, the mapping between cells and faces are required, which is defined by","title":"Physical space"},{"category":"type","location":"type_physical_space/#KitAMR.AbstractPsData","page":"Physical space","text":"abstract type AbstractPsData{DIM, NDF}\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.AbstractPsData"},{"category":"type","location":"type_physical_space/#KitAMR.PsData","page":"Physical space","text":"mutable struct PsData{DIM, NDF} <: AbstractPsData{DIM, NDF}\n\nquadid::Int32: Index of the quadrant corresponding to PsData.\nbound_enc::Int64: Encoding of the cell type. 0:fluid cell;>0: donor cell of bound_enc th immersed boundary;<0: solid cell (or solid neighbor) of bound_enc th boundary.\nsolid_cell_index::Vector{Int64}: Deprecated.\nds::Vector{Float64}: Faces area (length).\nmidpoint::Vector{Float64}: Coordinates of the cell center.\nqf::Vector{Float64}: Heat flux.\nw::Vector{Float64}: Conserved variables.\nsw::Matrix{Float64}: Gradients of conserved variables.\nprim::Vector{Float64}: Primary variables.\nflux::Vector{Float64}: Conserved flux.\nvs_data::VsData: Data of the velocity space.\nneighbor::Neighbor: Neighbor of the cell.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.PsData"},{"category":"type","location":"type_physical_space/#KitAMR.GhostPsData","page":"Physical space","text":"mutable struct GhostPsData{DIM, NDF} <: KitAMR.AbstractGhostPsData{DIM, NDF}\n\nowner_rank::Int64\nquadid::Int64\nbound_enc::Int64\nds::Vector{Float64}\nmidpoint::Vector{Float64}\nw::Vector{Float64}\nsw::Matrix{Float64}\nvs_data::GhostVsData\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.GhostPsData"},{"category":"type","location":"type_physical_space/#KitAMR.InsideSolidData","page":"Physical space","text":"mutable struct InsideSolidData{DIM, NDF} <: AbstractPsData{DIM, NDF}\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.InsideSolidData"},{"category":"type","location":"type_physical_space/#KitAMR.GhostInsideSolidData","page":"Physical space","text":"mutable struct GhostInsideSolidData{DIM, NDF} <: KitAMR.AbstractGhostPsData{DIM, NDF}\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.GhostInsideSolidData"},{"category":"type","location":"type_physical_space/#KitAMR.Neighbor","page":"Physical space","text":"mutable struct Neighbor{DIM, NDF}\n\ndata::Array{Array{Union{Nothing, AbstractPsData{DIM, NDF}}, 1}, 1} where {DIM, NDF}\nstate::Vector{Int64}\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.Neighbor"},{"category":"type","location":"type_physical_space/#KitAMR.SolidNeighbor","page":"Physical space","text":"mutable struct SolidNeighbor{DIM, NDF} <: AbstractPsData{DIM, NDF}\n\nbound_enc::Int64\nfaceid::Int64: Index of the face of the donor cell corresponding to this SolidNeighbor.\nav_id::Int64: Deprecated.\naux_point::Vector{Float64}: Intersect point at the boundary corresponding to this SolidNeighbor.\nnormal::Vector{Float64}: Normal vector of the boundary at aux_point.\nsolid_cell::AbstractPsData: Solid_cell corresponding to this SolidNeighbor.\nmidpoint::Vector{Float64}\nds::Vector{Float64}\nw::Vector{Float64}\nsw::Matrix{Float64}\ncvc::CuttedVelocityCells: Struct containing information of cut cell in velocity space.\nvs_data::VsData\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.SolidNeighbor"},{"category":"type","location":"type_physical_space/#KitAMR.AbstractFace","page":"Physical space","text":"abstract type AbstractFace\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.AbstractFace"},{"category":"type","location":"type_physical_space/#KitAMR.DomainFace","page":"Physical space","text":"struct DomainFace{DIM, NDF, T} <: KitAMR.BoundaryFace\n\nFace at the domain edge.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.DomainFace"},{"category":"type","location":"type_physical_space/#KitAMR.FullFace","page":"Physical space","text":"struct FullFace{DIM, NDF} <: KitAMR.InnerFace\n\nFace shared by cells with the same refinement level.\n\nrot::Float64: Rotational coefficient of the face. -1 if here_data locates at the negative direction relative to the face.\ndirection::Int64: Direction of the face's normal. 1, 2, 3 correspond to x, y, z respectively.\nmidpoint::Vector{Float64}: Coordinates of the face's center.\nhere_data::PsData: PsData on one side of the face. It is guaranteed to be local.\nthere_data::AbstractPsData: AbstractPsData on the other side of the face. It can be a ghost one.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.FullFace"},{"category":"type","location":"type_physical_space/#KitAMR.HangingFace","page":"Physical space","text":"struct HangingFace{DIM, NDF} <: KitAMR.InnerFace\n\nFaces shared by cells with different refinement levels. The cell with lower level is local.\n\nrot::Float64\ndirection::Int64\nmidpoint::Vector{Vector{Float64}}\nhere_data::PsData\nthere_data::Array{AbstractPsData{DIM, NDF}, 1} where {DIM, NDF}: AbstractPsDatas with higher refinement level.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.HangingFace"},{"category":"type","location":"type_physical_space/#KitAMR.BackHangingFace","page":"Physical space","text":"struct BackHangingFace{DIM, NDF} <: KitAMR.InnerFace\n\nFaces shared by cells with different refinement levels. The cell with lower level is ghost.\n\nrot::Float64\ndirection::Int64\nmidpoint::Vector{Vector{Float64}}\nhere_data::Array{PsData{DIM, NDF}, 1} where {DIM, NDF}\nthere_data::AbstractPsData\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.BackHangingFace"},{"category":"type","location":"type_physical_space/#KitAMR.FluxData","page":"Physical space","text":"struct FluxData{T<:KitAMR.InnerFace}\n\nStruct for flux calculation corresponding to a single face.\n\nrot::Float64\ndirection::Int64\nmidpoint::Vector{Float64}\nhere_data::AbstractPsData\nthere_data::AbstractPsData\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.FluxData"},{"category":"section","location":"type_gas/#Gas-properties","page":"Gas","text":"Struct that determines the properties of the simulated gas.","title":"Gas properties"},{"category":"type","location":"type_gas/#KitAMR.Gas","page":"Gas","text":"mutable struct Gas <: KitAMR.AbstractGas\n\nKn::Float64: Default is 0.05.\nPr::Float64: Default is 2/3.\nK::Float64: The translational internal DOF.Default is 1.0.\nγ::Float64: Default is 5/3.\nω::Float64: Default is 0.5.\nαᵣ::Float64: Default is 1.0.\nωᵣ::Float64: Default is 0.81.\nμᵣ::Float64: The reference viscosity. Default is computed by ref_vhs_vis.\nT_ref::Float64: The reference temperature of the molecular model. Default is 1.0.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.Gas"},{"category":"section","location":"methods_flux/#Flux","page":"Flux","text":"Numerical fluxes in KitAMR.jl are abstracted as\n\nTo distinguish with Navier-Stokes and other types of fluxes (which may be implemented in future version), the fluxes corresponding to DVM are abstracted to\n\nCurrently, the best supported flux is \n\nHere are functions related to flux calculation and update:","title":"Flux"},{"category":"section","location":"methods_flux/#Backend-functions","page":"Flux","text":"\n\nMethods for different types of faces. Through these methods, different scenarios are decomposed into a unified interface, and the same core functions can be invoked for solving.\n\n\n\nA shell for the dispatch according to whether the macro flux update is required. The method for DomainFace is separately defined: update_domain_flux!.\n\n\n\nRefer to update_flux!.\n\n\n\nUpdate flux in AbstractVsData. Mapping between velocity cells with different refinement level is considered.\n\n\n\nUpdate flux in AbstractPsData, which is necessary to predict the macroscopic state in implicit DVM. The conserved correction in the mapping between different velocity cells also depends on this.\n\n\n\nConstruct FaceVsData corresponding to here_data and there_data in AbstractFace.","title":"Backend functions"},{"category":"section","location":"methods_flux/#User-interfaces","page":"Flux","text":"Developers may hope to use their own numerical flux to meet their requirements. KitAMR.jl provides compact user interfaces. User only needs to define the flux across a single inner face and a single domain face. KitAMR.jl will automatically dispatch them for different mesh cases. As an example, the methods corresponding to CAIDVM are defined as\n\n\n\nCompute the flux across a single domain face. Methods for different types AbstractBoundCond of Domain are defined.\n\n\n\nA positivity preserving reconstruction is adopted when compute CAIDVM flux:","title":"User interfaces"},{"category":"type","location":"methods_flux/#KitAMR.AbstractFluxType","page":"Flux","text":"abstract type AbstractFluxType\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.AbstractFluxType"},{"category":"type","location":"methods_flux/#KitAMR.AbstractDVMFluxType","page":"Flux","text":"abstract type AbstractDVMFluxType <: AbstractFluxType\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.AbstractDVMFluxType"},{"category":"type","location":"methods_flux/#KitAMR.CAIDVM","page":"Flux","text":"abstract type CAIDVM <: AbstractDVMFluxType\n\nConserved adaptive implicit DVM flux.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.CAIDVM"},{"category":"method","location":"methods_flux/#KitAMR.flux!-Tuple{KA}","page":"Flux","text":"flux!(ka::KA)\n\n\nOuter function for flux computation and update. The iteration is carried out through faces, which avoids redundant computation.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.flux!"},{"category":"method","location":"methods_flux/#KitAMR.flux!-Tuple{DomainFace, KA}","page":"Flux","text":"flux!(face::DomainFace, ka::KA)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.flux!"},{"category":"method","location":"methods_flux/#KitAMR.flux!-Tuple{FullFace, KA}","page":"Flux","text":"flux!(face::FullFace, ka::KA)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.flux!"},{"category":"method","location":"methods_flux/#KitAMR.flux!-Union{Tuple{NDF}, Tuple{DIM}, Tuple{HangingFace{DIM, NDF}, KA}} where {DIM, NDF}","page":"Flux","text":"flux!(face::HangingFace{DIM, NDF}, ka::KA)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.flux!"},{"category":"method","location":"methods_flux/#KitAMR.flux!-Union{Tuple{NDF}, Tuple{DIM}, Tuple{BackHangingFace{DIM, NDF}, KA}} where {DIM, NDF}","page":"Flux","text":"flux!(face::BackHangingFace{DIM, NDF}, ka::KA)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.flux!"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_flux/#KitAMR.update_flux!","page":"Flux","text":"update_flux!(\n    flux::AbstractVector,\n    micro_flux::Vector{Matrix{Float64}},\n    face::Union{FluxData, FullFace},\n    heavi::Vector{Bool}\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\nupdate_flux!(\n    _::Nothing,\n    micro_flux::Vector{Matrix{Float64}},\n    face::Union{FluxData, FullFace},\n    heavi::Vector{Bool}\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.update_flux!"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_flux/#KitAMR.update_domain_flux!","page":"Flux","text":"update_domain_flux!(\n    flux::AbstractVector,\n    micro_flux::Vector{Matrix{Float64}},\n    face::DomainFace,\n    heavi::Vector{Bool}\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\nupdate_domain_flux!(\n    _::Nothing,\n    micro_flux::Vector{Matrix{Float64}},\n    face::DomainFace,\n    heavi::Vector{Bool}\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.update_domain_flux!"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_flux/#KitAMR.update_micro_flux!","page":"Flux","text":"update_micro_flux!(\n    here_micro,\n    there_micro,\n    here_data::PsData{DIM},\n    _::SolidNeighbor{DIM},\n    heavi::Vector{Bool}\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\nupdate_micro_flux!(\n    here_micro,\n    there_micro,\n    here_data::PsData{DIM, NDF},\n    there_data::PsData,\n    heavi::Vector{Bool}\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\nupdate_micro_flux!(\n    here_micro,\n    there_micro,\n    here_data::PsData{DIM, NDF},\n    there_data::KitAMR.AbstractGhostPsData,\n    heavi::Vector{Bool}\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.update_micro_flux!"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_flux/#KitAMR.update_macro_flux!","page":"Flux","text":"update_macro_flux!(\n    flux::Vector,\n    here_data::PsData,\n    there_data::PsData\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\nupdate_macro_flux!(\n    flux::Vector,\n    here_data::PsData,\n    _::KitAMR.AbstractGhostPsData\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\nupdate_macro_flux!(\n    flux::Vector,\n    here_data::PsData,\n    _::SolidNeighbor\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.update_macro_flux!"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_flux/#KitAMR.make_face_vs","page":"Flux","text":"make_face_vs(face::DomainFace{DIM, NDF}) -> FaceVsData\n\n\n\n\n\n\nmake_face_vs(\n    face::FullFace{DIM, NDF}\n) -> Tuple{FaceVsData, FaceVsData}\n\n\n\n\n\n\nmake_face_vs(\n    face::HangingFace{DIM, NDF}\n) -> Tuple{FaceVsData, Array{FaceVsData{_A, _B}, 1} where {_A, _B}}\n\n\n\n\n\n\nmake_face_vs(\n    face::BackHangingFace{DIM, NDF}\n) -> Tuple{Array{FaceVsData{_A, _B}, 1} where {_A, _B}, FaceVsData}\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.make_face_vs"},{"category":"method","location":"methods_flux/#KitAMR.calc_flux-Union{Tuple{NDF}, Tuple{DIM}, Tuple{Type{CAIDVM}, Any, Any, Union{FluxData, FullFace}, KA{DIM, NDF}}} where {DIM, NDF}","page":"Flux","text":"calc_flux(\n    _::Type{CAIDVM},\n    here_vs,\n    there_vs,\n    flux_data::Union{FluxData, FullFace},\n    ka::KA{DIM, NDF}\n) -> Tuple{Any, Any}\n\n\nCompute the flux across a single inner face. For CAIDVM, both macro and micro fluxes are computed.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.calc_flux"},{"category":"method","location":"methods_flux/#KitAMR.calc_domain_flux-Union{Tuple{NDF}, Tuple{DIM}, Tuple{Type{CAIDVM}, FaceVsData, DomainFace{DIM, NDF, Maxwellian}, KA}} where {DIM, NDF}","page":"Flux","text":"calc_domain_flux(\n    _::Type{CAIDVM},\n    here_vs::FaceVsData,\n    face::DomainFace{DIM, NDF, Maxwellian},\n    ka::KA\n) -> Tuple{Any, Any}\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.calc_domain_flux"},{"category":"method","location":"methods_flux/#KitAMR.calc_domain_flux-Union{Tuple{NDF}, Tuple{DIM}, Tuple{Type{CAIDVM}, FaceVsData, DomainFace{DIM, NDF, SuperSonicInflow}, KA}} where {DIM, NDF}","page":"Flux","text":"calc_domain_flux(\n    _::Type{CAIDVM},\n    here_vs::FaceVsData,\n    face::DomainFace{DIM, NDF, SuperSonicInflow},\n    ka::KA\n) -> Tuple{Any, Any}\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.calc_domain_flux"},{"category":"method","location":"methods_flux/#KitAMR.calc_domain_flux-Union{Tuple{NDF}, Tuple{DIM}, Tuple{Type{CAIDVM}, FaceVsData, DomainFace{DIM, NDF, UniformOutflow}, KA}} where {DIM, NDF}","page":"Flux","text":"calc_domain_flux(\n    _::Type{CAIDVM},\n    here_vs::FaceVsData,\n    face::DomainFace{DIM, NDF, UniformOutflow},\n    ka::KA\n) -> Tuple{Any, Any}\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.calc_domain_flux"},{"category":"method","location":"methods_flux/#KitAMR.calc_domain_flux-Union{Tuple{NDF}, Tuple{Type{CAIDVM}, FaceVsData, DomainFace{2, NDF, InterpolatedOutflow}, KA}} where NDF","page":"Flux","text":"calc_domain_flux(\n    _::Type{CAIDVM},\n    here_vs::FaceVsData,\n    face::DomainFace{2, NDF, InterpolatedOutflow},\n    ka::KA\n) -> Tuple{Any, Any}\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.calc_domain_flux"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_flux/#KitAMR.positivity_preserving_reconstruct","page":"Flux","text":"positivity_preserving_reconstruct(\n    here_df,\n    here_sdf,\n    here_ds,\n    dx,\n    vn\n) -> Any\n\n\nPositivity preserving reconstruction (10.1016/j.jcp.2009.12.030).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.positivity_preserving_reconstruct"},{"category":"section","location":"type_condition/#Initial-and-boundary-conditions","page":"Condition","text":"To launch a simulation, initial and boundary conditions are necessary.","title":"Initial and boundary conditions"},{"category":"section","location":"type_condition/#Initial-conditions","page":"Condition","text":"The types of initial conditions are abstracted as \n\nCurrently, available options are","title":"Initial conditions"},{"category":"section","location":"type_condition/#Boundary-conditions","page":"Condition","text":"The type of the boundary conditions is determined by \n\nCurrently, available options are\n\nWith these types of boundary conditions, \n\ncan be constructed. There are two types of the boundary.","title":"Boundary conditions"},{"category":"section","location":"type_condition/#Domain-boundary","page":"Condition","text":"KitAMR.jl always adopts square simulation domain. At the edges of the domain, proper conditions are required to maintain the well-posedness.","title":"Domain boundary"},{"category":"section","location":"type_condition/#Immersed-boundary","page":"Condition","text":"KitAMR.jl adopts the immersed boundary method (IBM) to resolve boundaries with complex geometry. To define the geometry, KitAMR.jl provides following interface.\n\nAs the special case, the cirlce in 2D and sphere in 3D are defined separately, and are abstracted as AbstractCircle=Union{Circle,Sphere}.\n\nFor other cases, KitAMR.jl read .csv file for 2D, which defines the vertices coordinates of the closed boundary curve; and .stl file for 3D, which provides the triangular discretization of the boundary surface. The example can be find in /example/airfoil and /example/X38 respectively.\n\nThe most common constructor is\n\nThe most common constructor is\n\nTriangleKDT is a struct containing information related to K-D tree for efficient mesh generation:","title":"Immersed boundary"},{"category":"type","location":"type_condition/#KitAMR.AbstractInitCond","page":"Condition","text":"abstract type AbstractInitCond\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.AbstractInitCond"},{"category":"type","location":"type_condition/#KitAMR.Uniform","page":"Condition","text":"struct Uniform <: AbstractInitCond\n\nUniform initial condition. The field will be initialized with the Maxwellian distribution determined by the unified primary macroscopic variables in ic.\n\nFields\n\nic::AbstractVector\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.Uniform"},{"category":"type","location":"type_condition/#KitAMR.PCoordFn","page":"Condition","text":"struct PCoordFn <: AbstractInitCond\n\nPhysical-coordinates-determined initial condition. The field will be initialized with the Maxwellian distribution determined by the user-defined-function in PCIC_fn. The function will return primary macroscopic variables vector according to the information of the physical grid (mostly the physical coordinates).\n\nFields\n\nPCIC_fn::Function\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.PCoordFn"},{"category":"type","location":"type_condition/#KitAMR.AbstractBoundCond","page":"Condition","text":"abstract type AbstractBoundCond\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.AbstractBoundCond"},{"category":"type","location":"type_condition/#KitAMR.Maxwellian","page":"Condition","text":"abstract type Maxwellian <: AbstractBoundCond\n\nFully diffused Maxwellian gas-surface interaction model.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.Maxwellian"},{"category":"type","location":"type_condition/#KitAMR.SuperSonicInflow","page":"Condition","text":"abstract type SuperSonicInflow <: AbstractBoundCond\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.SuperSonicInflow"},{"category":"type","location":"type_condition/#KitAMR.SuperSonicOutflow","page":"Condition","text":"abstract type SuperSonicOutflow <: AbstractBoundCond\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.SuperSonicOutflow"},{"category":"type","location":"type_condition/#KitAMR.UniformOutflow","page":"Condition","text":"abstract type UniformOutflow <: AbstractBoundCond\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.UniformOutflow"},{"category":"type","location":"type_condition/#KitAMR.InterpolatedOutflow","page":"Condition","text":"abstract type InterpolatedOutflow <: AbstractBoundCond\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.InterpolatedOutflow"},{"category":"type","location":"type_condition/#KitAMR.Period","page":"Condition","text":"abstract type Period <: AbstractBoundCond\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.Period"},{"category":"type","location":"type_condition/#KitAMR.AbstractBoundary","page":"Condition","text":"abstract type AbstractBoundary\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.AbstractBoundary"},{"category":"type","location":"type_condition/#KitAMR.Domain","page":"Condition","text":"struct Domain{T<:AbstractBoundCond} <: AbstractBoundary\n\nStructure of domain boundary.\n\nFields\n\nid::Int64: Index of the domain boundary. From 1 to 6, it represents the boundary of xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax, zmin, zmax.\nrefine::Bool: Whether refine at the domain boundary. Default is false.\nbc::Union{Function, Vector}: The boundary condition at the domain boundary.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.Domain"},{"category":"type","location":"type_condition/#KitAMR.Circle","page":"Condition","text":"struct Circle{T<:AbstractBoundCond} <: AbstractBoundary\n\ncenter::Vector: Center of the circle.\nradius::Real: Radius of the circle.\nsolid::Bool: Is solid inside the circle?\nsearch_coeffi::Real: Refinement coefficient.\nbc::Union{Function, Vector}: Primary macroscopic variables of the solid.\nsearch_radius::Real: Maximum distance of the refinement region from the boundary.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.Circle"},{"category":"type","location":"type_condition/#KitAMR.Sphere","page":"Condition","text":"struct Sphere{T<:AbstractBoundCond} <: AbstractBoundary\n\ncenter::Vector\nradius::Real\nsolid::Bool\nsearch_coeffi::Real\nbc::Union{Function, Vector}\nsearch_radius::Real\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.Sphere"},{"category":"type","location":"type_condition/#KitAMR.Vertices","page":"Condition","text":"struct Vertices{DIM, T<:AbstractBoundCond} <: AbstractBoundary\n\nvertices::Vector{Vector{Float64}}: Vertices of the boundary, sorted in clockwise or counterclockwise order.\nsolid::Bool\nbc::Union{Function, Vector}\nbox::Vector{Vector{Float64}}: The outer box of the vertices as [[xmin,ymin,zmin],[xmax,ymax,zmax]].\nsearch_radius::Real: The number of cell layers refined from the boundary.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.Vertices"},{"category":"method","location":"type_condition/#KitAMR.Vertices-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{Type{T}, String, Any, Any, Any}} where T<:AbstractBoundCond","page":"Condition","text":"Vertices(\n    _::Type{T<:AbstractBoundCond},\n    file::String,\n    solid,\n    refine_coeffi,\n    bc\n) -> Vertices\n\n\nfile is the path to the .csv file.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.Vertices"},{"category":"type","location":"type_condition/#KitAMR.Triangles","page":"Condition","text":"struct Triangles{T<:AbstractBoundCond} <: AbstractBoundary\n\nsolid::Bool\nbc::Union{Function, Vector}\nsearch_radius::Real\ntkdt::TriangleKDT\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.Triangles"},{"category":"method","location":"type_condition/#KitAMR.Triangles-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{Type{T}, String, Any, Any, Any}} where T<:AbstractBoundCond","page":"Condition","text":"Triangles(\n    _::Type{T<:AbstractBoundCond},\n    file::String,\n    solid,\n    search_radius,\n    bc\n) -> Triangles\n\n\nfile is the path to the .stl file.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.Triangles"},{"category":"type","location":"type_condition/#KitAMR.TriangleKDT","page":"Condition","text":"struct TriangleKDT\n\nkdt::NearestNeighbors.KDTree\nmesh::GeometryBasics.Mesh\ntable::Vector{NearestNeighbors.HyperRectangle{StaticArraysCore.SVector{3, Float64}}}\ntriangle_recs::Vector{NearestNeighbors.HyperRectangle{StaticArraysCore.SVector{3, Float64}}}\ntriangle_edges::Vector{Vector{StaticArraysCore.SVector{3, Float64}}}\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.TriangleKDT"},{"category":"section","location":"type_velocity_space/#Velocity-space","page":"Velocity space","text":"In kinetic methods, variables are also discretized in velocity space. Information in velocity space are separately stored in AbstractPsData, and are organized as following.","title":"Velocity space"},{"category":"type","location":"type_velocity_space/#KitAMR.AbstractVsData","page":"Velocity space","text":"abstract type AbstractVsData{DIM, NDF}\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.AbstractVsData"},{"category":"type","location":"type_velocity_space/#KitAMR.VsData","page":"Velocity space","text":"mutable struct VsData{DIM, NDF} <: AbstractVsData{DIM, NDF}\n\nvs_num::Int64: Number of velocity cells.\nlevel::Vector{Int8}: Refinement level of velocity cells.\nweight::Vector{Float64}: Quadrature weight of velocity cells.\nmidpoint::Matrix{Float64}: Coordinates of centers of velocity cells in velocity space.\ndf::Matrix{Float64}: Discretized distribution function.\nsdf::Array{Float64, 3}: Spatial gradients (df/dx) of distribution function.\nflux::Matrix{Float64}: Numerical flux of distribution function.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.VsData"},{"category":"type","location":"type_velocity_space/#KitAMR.GhostVsData","page":"Velocity space","text":"mutable struct GhostVsData{DIM, NDF} <: AbstractVsData{DIM, NDF}\n\nvs_num::Int64\nlevel::Vector{Int8}\nweight::Vector{Float64}\nmidpoint::Matrix{Float64}\ndf::Matrix{Float64}\nsdf::Array{Float64, 3}\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.GhostVsData"},{"category":"type","location":"type_velocity_space/#KitAMR.FaceVsData","page":"Velocity space","text":"struct FaceVsData{DIM, NDF}\n\nInformation of the velocity space corresponding to the face during the calculation of numerical flux.\n\nheavi::Vector{Bool}: Upwinding flags. Upwinding velocities are set to true.\nweight::AbstractVector{Float64}\nmidpoint::AbstractMatrix{Float64}\nvn::AbstractVector{Float64}: Normal component of velocities across the face.\ndf::AbstractMatrix{Float64}\nsdf::AbstractArray{Float64}\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.FaceVsData"},{"category":"type","location":"type_velocity_space/#KitAMR.CuttedVelocityCells","page":"Velocity space","text":"mutable struct CuttedVelocityCells\n\nStructure for cut cell in velocity space used in immersed boundaries.\n\nindices::Vector{Int64}: Indices of cut cells in SolidNeighbor's VsData.\nweight::Vector{Float64}: Quadrature weight of velocity cells. Specially, the weight of cut cells is set to 0.\ngas_dfs::Matrix{Float64}: Distribution function of gas part corresponding to velocity at the center of cut cells.\nsolid_dfs::Matrix{Float64}: Distribution function of solid part corresponding to velocity at the center of cut cells.\ngas_weights::Vector{Float64}: Areas of gas part in cut cells.\nsolid_weights::Vector{Float64}: Areas of solid part in cut cells.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.CuttedVelocityCells"},{"category":"section","location":"methods_finalize/#Finalization","page":"Finalization","text":"\n\n\n\nFinalize p4est things. Release the memory managed by C.","title":"Finalization"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_finalize/#KitAMR.residual_check!","page":"Finalization","text":"residual_check!(\n    ps_data::PsData,\n    prim::Vector{Float64},\n    kinfo::KInfo\n)\n\n\nUpdate residuals.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.residual_check!"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_finalize/#KitAMR.check_for_convergence","page":"Finalization","text":"check_for_convergence(ka)\n\n\nCheck whether the residual and redundant_step in Status satisfies the convergence criterion.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.check_for_convergence"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_finalize/#KitAMR.finalize!","page":"Finalization","text":"finalize!(p4est::Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p4est}, ka::KA)\n\n\n\n\n\n\nfinalize!(p4est::Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p8est}, ka::KA)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.finalize!"},{"category":"section","location":"methods_AMR/#Adaptive-mesh-refinement","page":"AMR","text":"AMR is the core functionality of KitAMR.jl. An integrated interface is provided","title":"Adaptive mesh refinement"},{"category":"section","location":"methods_AMR/#Physical-space","page":"AMR","text":"In physical space, a forest of quadtrees (for 2D) or octrees (for 3D) is constructed and managed with p4est.\n\n\n\nRefine cells satisfying criteria in physical space.\n\n\n\nCoarsen cells satisfying criteria in physical space.\n\n\n\nBalance mesh in physical space after refinement and coarsening. It ensures that the difference between the refinement levels of neighboring cells is not larger than 1.\n\n\n\nIn an AMR process, it is crucial to construct variables in newly generated cell (a larger one or a smaller one). Related methods are\n\n\n\nAMR criteria in physical space are defined by\n\nCurrently, KitAMR.jl decides according to the relative macroscopic gradient. To compute this, a globally maximum gradient is obtained by","title":"Physical space"},{"category":"section","location":"methods_AMR/#Velocity-space","page":"AMR","text":"In velocity space, considering the enormous number of the phase grids, constructing a forest in velocity space for every physical cell is impossible. Hence, the AMR in velocity space is more elaborately designed.\n\nRelated functions are\n\nThe replacement functions are more particular and are planted inside the adaptation functions.\n\nCompared with the AMR in physical space, the conservation is not automatically maintained in velocity space. Hence, a correction is required\n\nThe refinement and coarsening in velocity space are decided according to the relative contribution of the velocity cell to the macroscopic quantities. Currently, mass and energy are considered.\n\nThe contribution is measured from two points of view. The global one is related to the globally maximum resolution of a velocity cell. The local one tells the proportion in the conserved variables in the local physical cell.\n\n","title":"Velocity space"},{"category":"section","location":"methods_AMR/#Recovery","page":"AMR","text":"After an AMR process, the mesh has been changed a lot. The ghost layers,  neighbor relations, immersed boundaries, and faces are required to be reconstructed.\n\nCurrently, the recovery function is yet to be optimized for higher efficiency. However, the overhead is negligible.","title":"Recovery"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_AMR/#KitAMR.adaptive_mesh_refinement!","page":"AMR","text":"adaptive_mesh_refinement!(\n    p4est::Union{Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p4est}, Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p8est}},\n    ka::KA;\n    ps_interval,\n    vs_interval,\n    partition_interval,\n    ps_recursive,\n    vs_balance\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.adaptive_mesh_refinement!"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_AMR/#KitAMR.ps_adaptive_mesh_refinement!","page":"AMR","text":"ps_adaptive_mesh_refinement!(\n    p4est::Union{Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p4est}, Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p8est}},\n    ka::KA;\n    recursive\n)\n\n\nOuter function of AMR in physical space.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.ps_adaptive_mesh_refinement!"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_AMR/#KitAMR.ps_refine!","page":"AMR","text":"ps_refine!(\n    p4est::Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p4est},\n    ka::KA;\n    recursive\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\nps_refine!(\n    p4est::Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p8est},\n    ka::KA;\n    recursive\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.ps_refine!"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_AMR/#KitAMR.ps_coarsen!","page":"AMR","text":"ps_coarsen!(\n    p4est::Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p4est};\n    recursive\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\nps_coarsen!(\n    p4est::Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p8est};\n    recursive\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.ps_coarsen!"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_AMR/#KitAMR.ps_balance!","page":"AMR","text":"ps_balance!(p4est::Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p4est})\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.ps_balance!"},{"category":"method","location":"methods_AMR/#KitAMR.ps_replace!-Union{Tuple{DIM}, Tuple{Val{1}, Any, Any, Any, KA{DIM}}} where DIM","page":"AMR","text":"ps_replace!(\n    _::Val{1},\n    out_quad,\n    in_quads,\n    which_tree,\n    ka::KA{DIM}\n)\n\n\nReplacement function in a refinement process.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.ps_replace!"},{"category":"method","location":"methods_AMR/#KitAMR.ps_replace!-Union{Tuple{NDF}, Tuple{DIM}, Tuple{Union{Val{4}, Val{8}}, Any, Any, Any, KA{DIM, NDF}}} where {DIM, NDF}","page":"AMR","text":"ps_replace!(\n    _::Union{Val{4}, Val{8}},\n    out_quad,\n    in_quads,\n    which_tree,\n    ka::KA{DIM, NDF}\n)\n\n\nReplacement function in a coarsening process.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.ps_replace!"},{"category":"method","location":"methods_AMR/#KitAMR.ps_refine_flag-Union{Tuple{DIM}, Tuple{PsData{DIM}, KA{DIM}, Union{KitAMR.P4est.PointerWrappers.PointerWrapper{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p4est_quadrant}, KitAMR.P4est.PointerWrappers.PointerWrapper{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p8est_quadrant}}}} where DIM","page":"AMR","text":"ps_refine_flag(\n    ps_data::PsData{DIM},\n    ka::KA{DIM},\n    qp::Union{KitAMR.P4est.PointerWrappers.PointerWrapper{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p4est_quadrant}, KitAMR.P4est.PointerWrappers.PointerWrapper{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p8est_quadrant}}\n) -> Int32\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.ps_refine_flag"},{"category":"method","location":"methods_AMR/#KitAMR.ps_coarsen_flag-Union{Tuple{NDF}, Tuple{DIM}, Tuple{Vector{PsData}, Vector{Int64}, KA{DIM, NDF}}} where {DIM, NDF}","page":"AMR","text":"ps_coarsen_flag(\n    ps_datas::Vector{PsData},\n    levels::Vector{Int64},\n    ka::KA{DIM, NDF}\n) -> Int32\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.ps_coarsen_flag"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_AMR/#KitAMR.update_gradmax!","page":"AMR","text":"update_gradmax!(ka::KA{DIM})\n\n\nUpdate the globally maximum gradients of conserved variables as a referrence of the AMR in physical space.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.update_gradmax!"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_AMR/#KitAMR.vs_adaptive_mesh_refinement!","page":"AMR","text":"vs_adaptive_mesh_refinement!(ka; vs_balance)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.vs_adaptive_mesh_refinement!"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_AMR/#KitAMR.vs_refine!","page":"AMR","text":"vs_refine!(\n    va_data::KitAMR.Velocity_Adaptive_Data,\n    ka::KA{DIM, NDF}\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.vs_refine!"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_AMR/#KitAMR.vs_coarsen!","page":"AMR","text":"vs_coarsen!(\n    va_data::KitAMR.Velocity_Adaptive_Data,\n    ka::KA{DIM, NDF}\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.vs_coarsen!"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_AMR/#KitAMR.vs_conserved_correction!","page":"AMR","text":"vs_conserved_correction!(\n    va_data::KitAMR.Velocity_Adaptive_Data,\n    ka\n)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.vs_conserved_correction!"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_AMR/#KitAMR.contribution_refine_flag","page":"AMR","text":"contribution_refine_flag(\n    w::AbstractVector,\n    U::AbstractVector,\n    midpoint::AbstractVector,\n    df::AbstractVector,\n    weight::Float64,\n    vr::KitAMR.Velocity_Resolution,\n    kinfo::KInfo\n) -> Any\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.contribution_refine_flag"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_AMR/#KitAMR.contribution_coarsen_flag","page":"AMR","text":"contribution_coarsen_flag(\n    w::AbstractVector,\n    U::AbstractVector,\n    midpoint::AbstractMatrix,\n    df::AbstractMatrix,\n    weight::AbstractVector,\n    vr::KitAMR.Velocity_Resolution,\n    kinfo::KInfo\n) -> Bool\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.contribution_coarsen_flag"},{"category":"function","location":"methods_AMR/#KitAMR.amr_recover!","page":"AMR","text":"amr_recover!(\n    p4est::Union{Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p4est}, Ptr{KitAMR.P4est.LibP4est.p8est}},\n    ka::KA\n)\n\n\nRecover the ghost layers, neighbor relations, immersed boundaries, and faces after an AMR or partition process.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.amr_recover!"},{"category":"section","location":"#KitAMR.jl","page":"Home","text":"","title":"KitAMR.jl"},{"category":"section","location":"#Motivation","page":"Home","text":"KitAMR.jl is a distributed adaptive Cartesian grid solver for kinetic equations, developed based on P4est.jl. Its goal is to achieve large-scale parallel solving of 2D and 3D flows across all regimes, leveraging GPUs, differentiable programming, and machine learning to enhance solving efficiency.\n\nFor 1.0 version, we enable the solver to determinately simulate rarefied flows with high efficiency. The following functionalities have been implemented:\n\nPhysical mesh generation for arbitrary boundary geometry;\nImmersed boundary method for Maxwellian gas-surface interaction model;\nGeometric adaptation of physical space grids;\nDynamic adaptation of physical space grids;\nDynamic adaptation of velocity space grids;\nDistributed parallelism on CPUs;\nLoad balancing based on phase space grid density;\nLinear reconstruction with second-order spatial accuracy;\nComposite Newton-Cotes rule with second-order quadrature accuracy;\nVTK&JLD output for post-processing.\n\nAll of the funcationalities are applicable to both 2D and 3D cases.\n\n<div align=\"center\">\n    <div style=\"display: flex; gap: 20px;  width: 100%;\">\n        <div style=\"flex: 1; \">\n            <img \n            src=\"assets/X38_Temperature_z.svg\"  \n            style=\"width: 100%; aspect-ratio: 1/1;  border: none;\">\n        </div>\n        <div style=\"flex: 1;\">\n            <img \n            src=\"assets/X38_Temperature_contour_y.svg\"\n            style=\"width: 100%; aspect-ratio: 1/1; border: none;\">\n        </div>\n        <div style=\"flex: 1;\">\n            <img \n            src=\"assets/X38_surf_P.svg\"\n            style=\"width: 100%; aspect-ratio: 1/1; border: none;\">\n        </div>\n    </div>\n    <figcaption><i>A flow over X-38 model with Ma=8, Kn=0.275 simulated by KitAMR.jl.</i></figcaption>\n</div>","title":"Motivation"},{"category":"section","location":"#Theory","page":"Home","text":"","title":"Theory"},{"category":"section","location":"#Kinetic-Methods","page":"Home","text":"In kinetic theory, methods simulate the macroscopic motion of fluids by describing the evolution of distribution functions of fluid particles in velocity space over time. Such methods include direct simulation Monte Carlo (DSMC), discrete velocity method (DVM), lattice Boltzmann equation (LBE), gas-kinetic scheme, semi-Lagrangian method, implicit-explicit (IMEX) method, and others.","title":"Kinetic Methods"},{"category":"section","location":"#Distribution-Function","page":"Home","text":"In kinetic methods, the state of the fluid is described by a distribution function f(mathbfxmathbfut). The distribution function represents the number of particles at a given moment in time at a specific physical space point in a particular velocity space element. Its normalization property is\n\nrho(mathbfxt)=iiint_-infty^inftyf(mathbfxmathbfut)dmathbfu\n\n, where rho(mathbfxt) is the density of flows at mathbfx in time t. At higher temperatures, molecular internal degrees of freedom are excited, and the distribution function will depend on these degrees of freedom as well. For simplicity, we do not currently consider this situation.\n\n<div align=\"center\">\n    <img src=\"assets/distribution.jpg\" alt=\"Image 1\" width=\"300\" style=\"margin-right: 1px;\">\n    <figcaption><i>The distribution function in 2D velocity space.</i></figcaption>\n</div>\n\nWith the distribution function, macroscopic conservative variables can be caculated as follows:\n\nbeginsplit\nrho = iiint_-infty^inftyf(mathbfxmathbfut)dmathbfu\nrhomathbf U = iiint_-infty^inftymathbf uf(mathbfxmathbfut)dmathbfu\nrho E = iiint_-infty^infty frac 12 mathbf u^2f(mathbfxmathbfut)dmathbfu\nmathbf q=iiint_-infty^infty mathbf ufrac 12 mathbf u^2f(mathbfxmathbfut)dmathbfu\nendsplit","title":"Distribution Function"},{"category":"section","location":"#Boltzmann-Equation","page":"Home","text":"The evolution of the distribution function follows the Boltzmann equation.\n\nfracpartial fpartial t+mathbfucdotfracpartial fpartial mathbfx+mathbfFcdotfracpartial fpartial mathbfu=iiint_-infty^inftyint_0^4pi(f^*f_1^*-ff_1)c_rsigma dOmega dc_1\n\nThe Boltzmann equation holds a central position in kinetic theory, which is an integro-differential equation, with a four-fold integral term on the right-hand side. The complexity introduced by this term makes solving the Boltzmann equation challenging. Therefore, as a simplification, kinetic methods often solve its model equations instead.","title":"Boltzmann Equation"},{"category":"section","location":"#Shakhov-Model-Equation","page":"Home","text":"The simplified equation obtained after simplifying the collision term is known as the Shakhov model equation:\n\nbegincases\nfracpartial fpartial t+mathbfucdotfracpartial fpartial mathbfx+mathbfFcdotfracpartial fpartial mathbfu=fracg^+-ftau\ng^+=g1+frac45(1-mathrmPr)lambda^2fracmathbfucdotmathbfqrho(2lambda mathbfu^2-5)\nendcases\n\n, Where mathrm Pr is the Prandtl number, mathbfq is the heat flux, and tau is the relaxation time typically given through phenomenological models to match experimental data. The Shakhov model can provide results close to the Boltzmann equation for mass, momentum, energy, and heat fluxes in situations where flow velocities are not very high and deviations from equilibrium are not very large. And the current solver is based on Shakhov model.","title":"Shakhov Model Equation"},{"category":"section","location":"#Computing-Methods","page":"Home","text":"","title":"Computing Methods"},{"category":"section","location":"#Finite-Volume-Method-(FVM)","page":"Home","text":"The underlying discretization of the Boltzmann equation is based on finite volume method, with its discrete form as follows:\n\noverline U_jOmega_j^n+1 = \noverline U_j Omega_j^n-Delta tsum_partialOmegamathbfF^*cdotDeltamathbfS+Delta t overlineQ_jOmega_j\n\n, where overline U_j^ncoloneqqfrac1Omega_jint_Omega_jUdOmega_j^n, overline Q_j^ncoloneqqfrac1Omega_jint_Omega_jQdOmega_j are the cell-averaged conservative variable and source. And overline Q_j^* and mathbfF^* are respectively cell- and time-averaged sources and numerical flux, which are defined as overline Q_j^*coloneqqfrac1Delta tint_n^n+1overline Q_jdt and mathbf F^*cdot Delta mathbfScoloneqq frac1Delta tint_n^n+1mathbf FcdotDelta mathbfSdt. It is an exact relation for the time evolution of the space averaged conservative avriables over cell j from time step n to n+1. And the numerical flux mathbf F^* identifies completely a scheme by the way it approximates the time-averaged physical flux along each cell face.","title":"Finite Volume Method (FVM)"},{"category":"section","location":"#Numerical-Flux","page":"Home","text":"Currently the best supported numerical flux is the semi-implicit DVM, with interface variables obtained from linear reconsitruction with the VanLeer limiter. For specific implementation details, please refer to the relevant literature.","title":"Numerical Flux"},{"category":"section","location":"#Discrete-Velocity-Method","page":"Home","text":"DVM is one of the popular approaches for solving rarefied flow problems. In this method, the particle velocity space is discretized into a finite set of points and the numerical quadrature rule is utilized to approximate the integration of moments. Since the particle velocity space is discretized into a finite set of points, the continuum Boltzmann equation is reduced to the corresponding discrete velocity Boltzmann equation (DVBE). Based on the original DVM, great variety of algorithms have been developed, including unified gas-kinetic scheme (UGKS), discrete unified gas-kinetic scheme (DUGKS), semi-Lagrangian method, etc. Most of the above methods can be applied from free molecular regime to continuum regime. But in order to make the quadrature error to be small enough, a large number of discrete velocity points are usually required. In particular, for fluid flows near continuum regime, the computational cost of DVM is much larger than those traditional CFD methods based on the Navier-Stokes equation.","title":"Discrete Velocity Method"},{"category":"section","location":"#Adaptive-Mesh-Refinement-(AMR)","page":"Home","text":"Considering the above limitation of DVM, we adopt Adaptive Mesh Refinement (AMR) to improve solving efficiency. AMR reallocates computational resources based on flow features, balancing efficiency and accuracy. \n\n<div align=\"center\">\n    <img src=\"assets/AMR.gif\" alt=\"Image 1\" width = \"600\" style=\"margin-left: 1px;\">\n    <figcaption><i>Hypersonic rarefied flow over a cylinder. The simultaneous AMR in physical space (left) and velocity space (right) are performed.</i></figcaption>\n</div>\n\nThe current solver discretizes with tree-based Cartesian grids, adapting the mesh in both physical and velocity space simultaneously, according to characteristics like conserved variables' gradients and the mass and energy proportion at the velocity collocations. Users can also customize the criteria for grid refinement or coarsening according to their own needs.\n\nFor an AMR solver, the load-balance ability is crucial for high efficiency. KitAMR.jl inherits the load-balance functionality in p4est. The domain decomposition is performed in physical space. The physical grids are encoded into a 1-dimensional sequence by Morton code, and are partitioned to maintain the phase grids number on each processor approximately equal.\n\n<div align=\"center\">\n    <img src=\"assets/partition.gif\" alt=\"Image 1\" width = \"600\" style=\"margin-left: 1px;\">\n    <figcaption><i>The variation of the processor rank in physical domain during a simulation.</i></figcaption>\n</div>","title":"Adaptive Mesh Refinement (AMR)"},{"category":"section","location":"#Cartesian-Grids","page":"Home","text":"Cartesian grids offer advantages such as high grid quality, automated mesh generation, nature of the parallelism and capability for dynamic adaptation, but struggle with complex boundary geometries. To address this challenge, we developed an Immersed Boundary Method (IBM) for the discrete velocity model of the Boltzmann equation, which has been planted in KitAMR.jl. For more details, you may refer to our paper: https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.2512.20252.","title":"Cartesian Grids"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorial/#Tutorial","page":"Tutorial","text":"","title":"Tutorial"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorial/#Installation","page":"Tutorial","text":"In your personal workstation, the installation of KitAMR.jl is quite simple. Just run\n\njulia> ]\n(//your_julia_version//) pkg> activate .\n(//your_path//) pkg> add KitAMR\n\nFor cluster environment, preliminary procedure is required to deploy a local p4est, which enable KitAMR.jl to use the optimized MPI backend on cluster.","title":"Installation"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorial/#Utilization","page":"Tutorial","text":"To launch a simulation, user is required to execute a Julia script from the command line in an MPI manner. Examples can be found in /example. Here we show one of them and provide detailed explanation.","title":"Utilization"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorial/#X-38-spacecraft","page":"Tutorial","text":"In KitAMR.jl, user-provided configuration can be input in two approaches. \n\nThe first one is to define a .txt file, that is /example/X38/configure_X38.txt. The file will be read by read_config and returned as a dictionary. In the file, names in front of = are required to be consistent with the fieldnames of Configure type and the types in its field (including Gas, Solver, Output, and UDF). The meaning of these fields can be referred to the definition of these types in Type pages.\n\nThe other one is to construct the Configure directly in .jl script.\n\nThe scripts in these two approaches are respectively given by /example/X38/X38_text.jl and /example/X38/X38_julia.jl.\n\nThe initial conditions function in PCoordFn and other user-defined functions in UDF are collected in /example/X38/X38_udf.jl.\n\nThe geometry of the immersed boundary is defined in /example/X38/X38_normalized.stl.\n\nFor other information, one may refer to the comments in /example/X38/X38_julia.jl.","title":"X-38 spacecraft"},{"category":"section","location":"methods_iterate/#Iteration","page":"Iteration","text":"In kinetic methods, time marching is commonly coupled with collision process. The time marching scheme as well as the realization of collision process is abstracted as\n\nThe best supported time marching type is\n\nIn this type, time derivative is dicretized with backward Euler method, exhibiting first order accuracy. Collision process is carried out with conserved correction, which is crucial for AMR in velocity space.\n\n\n\nHere are the related functions:\n\n\n\nDeveloper may hope to define their own collision process. As an example, the method for CAIDVM_Marching is defined as","title":"Iteration"},{"category":"type","location":"methods_iterate/#KitAMR.AbstractTimeMarchingType","page":"Iteration","text":"abstract type AbstractTimeMarchingType\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.AbstractTimeMarchingType"},{"category":"type","location":"methods_iterate/#KitAMR.CAIDVM_Marching","page":"Iteration","text":"abstract type CAIDVM_Marching <: AbstractTimeMarchingType\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.CAIDVM_Marching"},{"category":"method","location":"methods_iterate/#KitAMR.iterate!-Tuple{KA}","page":"Iteration","text":"iterate!(ka::KA)\n\n\nOuter function of collision and time marching.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.iterate!"},{"category":"method","location":"methods_iterate/#KitAMR.iterate!-Tuple{Type{CAIDVM_Marching}, KA}","page":"Iteration","text":"iterate!(_::Type{CAIDVM_Marching}, ka::KA)\n\n\nIteration for Conserved Adaptive Implicit DVM (CAIDVM).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"KitAMR.iterate!"}]
}
